1
00:00:01,110 --> 00:00:27,522
namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassa namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassa namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:27,503 --> 00:00:32,009
homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:34,371 --> 00:00:38,235
So just an opportunity to just reflect on the Buddha's life.

4
00:00:38,356 --> 00:00:50,271
We all know, I think most of us know the general outlay of the life, but just to contemplate it a little and to see how it fits in with this

5
00:00:50,250 --> 00:00:52,735
taking of refuges and precepts.

6
00:00:52,756 --> 00:00:59,950
So remember... Could you open that window, Ruth?

7
00:01:01,093 --> 00:01:09,930
Remember that he belonged to this warrior class, the Kshatriya class, which would be...

8
00:01:10,501 --> 00:01:33,167
sort of landed gentry really and with plenty of time on their hands unlike the the workers of course in those days they lived according to the seasons there was always one season where you don't do much you know like the dry season and the winter season and all that but even so he would have had a much more relaxed and easy life than most people of his time and

9
00:01:34,344 --> 00:01:42,415
If we try to match it with ourselves, our society,

10
00:01:42,968 --> 00:01:46,231
seeking for distraction, seeking for pleasure all the time.

11
00:01:46,873 --> 00:02:01,673
And this comes out in one of his little tales, remember, when he wakes up in the morning after an all-night revelling and just sees all these people in disgusting positions and whatnot, and he sort of turns him off.

12
00:02:01,853 --> 00:02:07,221
I mean, that's one of the things, the evanescence or the emptiness of sensual pleasure.

13
00:02:08,298 --> 00:02:16,372
The other story, of course, is about meeting these four messengers from the gods, as they're known.

14
00:02:16,491 --> 00:02:28,432
Basically, he becomes much more aware of sickness, old age, and death, and the fact that there are people who seem to be sitting under trees, and he wonders what they're about.

15
00:02:28,581 --> 00:02:34,176
And there's a suggestion with the ascetics that there may be a way out of this constant rebirth.

16
00:02:34,236 --> 00:02:43,603
So remember in his day, the idea, well, as in India and the East today, it's taken for granted that there is a rebirthing process from life after life.

17
00:02:43,582 --> 00:03:06,566
So that had a very poignant feeling for him because what was up for a being was this constant being reborn into lifetimes and lifetimes of being born, growing, sickness, old age, death, being born, grown, sickness, old age and death.

18
00:03:06,906 --> 00:03:09,709
And it seems to have been an obsession of the times.

19
00:03:09,688 --> 00:03:21,883
And there was a movement of the times where more and more men, mainly, were just leaving the home life and going off to do these various practices.

20
00:03:22,383 --> 00:03:24,906
And there were various practices which were on offer.

21
00:03:25,787 --> 00:03:35,578
But when he left home, the one that he seemed to move towards were what came to be known as the jhanas, these absorption states.

22
00:03:36,723 --> 00:03:38,705
That was seemingly his first effort.

23
00:03:39,906 --> 00:03:48,213
And the idea there was that you can create this internal happiness without anything from the outside.

24
00:03:48,995 --> 00:03:59,526
So, practicing metta, for instance, we can keep making that intention until the heart responds, and eventually you're just filled with this inner bliss, this inner ecstasy, you might say.

25
00:04:00,467 --> 00:04:02,508
And once you can do that, well, it's all right, isn't it?

26
00:04:02,528 --> 00:04:03,409
You can sit under a tree.

27
00:04:03,569 --> 00:04:05,852
You don't mind eating rotten sausages.

28
00:04:05,831 --> 00:04:07,438
anything like that, or cold chips.

29
00:04:07,901 --> 00:04:08,484
Doesn't matter, does it?

30
00:04:08,865 --> 00:04:15,133
You can just sit under a tea and be happy any time you want because it's there within your power to create a beautiful mental state.

31
00:04:15,889 --> 00:04:39,197
But on both occasions, with both teachers who took him into these various different levels of ecstasy, he always came out and seemingly rediscovered the same old sad, depressed, anxious Siddhartha Gautama, like nothing had really moved at the level of his psychology, nothing had been cleansed, and he was still worried about it all, I presume.

32
00:04:39,548 --> 00:05:07,834
and then he tries mortification exercises and the idea there is that the real problem is the body so if you think about it if the body never felt hungry you wouldn't feel greed so basically you stop eating and you just eat bits of rice and stuff like that and as long as you keep your body appetites down then you don't get the problems with sensual pleasure but he discovered that the only thing he gained from that was basically became thin

33
00:05:08,084 --> 00:05:10,968
And it was nothing but more suffering.

34
00:05:10,988 --> 00:05:13,274
He didn't actually gain anything from that at all.

35
00:05:13,314 --> 00:05:17,661
He said it was unprofitable, ignoble and suffering.

36
00:05:18,302 --> 00:05:25,536
So he left that, if you remember, and to the disgust of his five companions, because they were still all for it.

37
00:05:26,916 --> 00:05:36,608
And he's sitting by the roadside there when Sujata comes along with an offering of some sort of rice pudding, which he takes.

38
00:05:36,668 --> 00:05:42,196
It seems to have revived him a bit, as you know rice pudding can.

39
00:05:42,216 --> 00:05:49,144
And this is when he remembers this occasion in childhood, and this is why we say he's self-enlightened.

40
00:05:49,512 --> 00:05:56,288
Up until then he's tried all these different means and ways and it's not really got him anywhere.

41
00:05:56,829 --> 00:06:07,334
But it's this memory from childhood which opens up for him a possibility of investigating his condition.

42
00:06:07,619 --> 00:06:11,346
And the memory is of watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

43
00:06:11,786 --> 00:06:26,175
But it's the manner of watching, you see, that childlike curiosity, which he then takes with him under this tree, making a very clear resolution that he was either going to crack this one or die.

44
00:06:26,216 --> 00:06:28,259
That's a pretty heavy evolution, isn't it?

45
00:06:28,713 --> 00:06:38,949
And luckily for those and for him, six hours on, he sort of makes this wonderful insight, this wonderful understanding.

46
00:06:41,875 --> 00:06:55,497
And that curiosity, that awareness and curiosity, the way of looking, then becomes the very technique that he passes on to other people, and we call that vipassana.

47
00:06:56,252 --> 00:07:06,350
What we're celebrating on a day like this is the effort that this person made 2500 years ago to seek the end of suffering.

48
00:07:06,370 --> 00:07:15,627
And when he came to encapsulate all his teaching, you know, 40 years of talking to people about his understanding

49
00:07:15,810 --> 00:07:23,744
he could draw it down in the Pali just to three words, suffering and the end of suffering, dukkha and the end of dukkha.

50
00:07:24,324 --> 00:07:36,925
So this dukkha, remember, is a very wide meaning, it's not just suffering as we would normally call it, it's dissatisfaction, it's existential angst, you know, even the mildest discomfort all happens to be dukkha, you know.

51
00:07:38,947 --> 00:07:43,353
and he spends the rest of his life teaching this.

52
00:07:43,834 --> 00:08:00,218
So this is, I think, very important to grasp that the awakening that came to him didn't pull him out of existence, didn't sort of make him sit there, you know, like a useless log or something.

53
00:08:01,278 --> 00:08:02,401
He then got up.

54
00:08:02,420 --> 00:08:08,649
There was a movement of that wisdom down into an attitude and into an action.

55
00:08:08,932 --> 00:08:13,367
So the wisdom became compassion, just as an outward flow.

56
00:08:15,072 --> 00:08:21,694
Logically speaking, there's no reason why he should have done it, apart from the fact of that empathy with all beings.

57
00:08:22,653 --> 00:08:27,117
And as you know, there was a moment of doubt as to whether anybody would understand it.

58
00:08:27,898 --> 00:08:32,863
And some people translate that as a doubt as to whether he would teach or not.

59
00:08:32,964 --> 00:08:33,924
But I don't think that's right.

60
00:08:33,985 --> 00:08:38,729
I think it's the doubt really as to whether anybody would understand it or not.

61
00:08:39,389 --> 00:08:42,052
He definitely wanted to pass on this message.

62
00:08:42,913 --> 00:08:50,061
And he walks quite away, doesn't he, from Bodh Gaya to Isiputana Park to catch up with his old companions.

63
00:08:51,559 --> 00:08:58,249
When he gets to his old companions, of course, they think he's just become lax and he's lost it.

64
00:08:58,669 --> 00:09:03,176
So they don't really greet him with any friendliness or anything.

65
00:09:03,255 --> 00:09:10,285
But as he comes towards them, they see something's different about him and actually prepare a seat for him as if he's a teacher.

66
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:20,841
Now, it's very interesting because when he talks to them in the first beginning, what is recorded is he asks them, he says, have you ever heard me talking like this before?

67
00:09:21,630 --> 00:09:37,033
So in other words, he's asking them, having displayed his teaching as best as he can, this is his first effort, you might say, and he's asking them, have you ever heard me say anything like this before?

68
00:09:37,394 --> 00:09:41,902
And that's what convinces them to practice with him.

69
00:09:42,361 --> 00:09:48,751
And the four of them eventually become fully liberated through his teachings.

70
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:59,311
So when we take the refuge, in terms of taking refuge in the Buddha, that's what we're taking refuge in.

71
00:09:59,331 --> 00:10:05,618
We're taking refuge in a personage and the truth of his message, which is the Dharma.

72
00:10:06,558 --> 00:10:14,267
And those people who after him were able to liberate themselves and become witnesses of that very teaching.

73
00:10:15,243 --> 00:10:19,890
So those are your three refuges in, shall we say, the traditional way.

74
00:10:20,672 --> 00:10:25,379
The tradition is that we're taking refuge in this personage.

75
00:10:25,399 --> 00:10:30,990
And this personage is not only our exemplar, remember, he's actually an archetype.

76
00:10:31,476 --> 00:10:38,287
in the sense that we all have to travel through that same path in our own way to become fully liberated.

77
00:10:38,606 --> 00:10:45,216
So we have to eventually renounce the world as a place where we can find permanent happiness.

78
00:10:45,998 --> 00:10:56,673
So long as there's a part of us seeking happiness in the phenomenal world, there'll be no escape from the problems that indulgence brings to us.

79
00:10:56,653 --> 00:11:01,842
So at some point through our practice, there has to be this renunciation.

80
00:11:02,825 --> 00:11:08,434
That scares people because you think, well, I'll just end up being a prune-like ascetic.

81
00:11:09,376 --> 00:11:12,422
I'll end up being just a dried prune.

82
00:11:13,604 --> 00:11:18,493
That's not very attractive, is it?

83
00:11:18,912 --> 00:11:29,039
But it wouldn't be if it weren't that, of course, as you give up something, you receive something back, which are the spiritual gifts.

84
00:11:29,188 --> 00:11:38,547
And the obvious ones are the seven factors of enlightenment which include calmness, equanimity, this joy that comes with interest.

85
00:11:39,207 --> 00:11:49,527
And the heart then responds, begins to express in its attitude the wisdom you have and you end up with this beautiful heart, this beautiful mind.

86
00:11:49,506 --> 00:11:54,333
especially in the four illimitables, love, compassion, joy and peace.

87
00:11:55,034 --> 00:12:00,482
And then that flows outward into the way you speak, into what you do and into your livelihood.

88
00:12:01,003 --> 00:12:06,049
So, it's not as though we're giving something up for nothing.

89
00:12:06,171 --> 00:12:09,995
We're actually giving something up for something which is far greater

90
00:12:09,975 --> 00:12:16,264
The problem is that you don't know really what you're going to get until you give something up.

91
00:12:17,166 --> 00:12:22,793
So remember, it's not like getting rid of your old TV or something and you know which one you're going to get, the new plasma.

92
00:12:23,375 --> 00:12:25,899
I mean, that's pretty strange.

93
00:12:26,158 --> 00:12:28,322
There's no angst there, is there?

94
00:12:29,551 --> 00:12:33,057
But unfortunately, in the spiritual life, you don't quite know what you're going to get when you give something up.

95
00:12:33,376 --> 00:12:37,182
And you have to actually give it up before you get something.

96
00:12:37,604 --> 00:12:41,009
And it's not as though you can half give it up.

97
00:12:41,249 --> 00:12:43,793
You know, say, well, I'll give it up a little bit and just see what's coming.

98
00:12:45,996 --> 00:12:47,700
But then nothing much comes.

99
00:12:47,759 --> 00:12:54,309
There has to be a sort of renunciation of seeking happiness in the sensual world.

100
00:12:55,657 --> 00:12:59,441
But again, we all do it in our own time.

101
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:00,702
There's no rush about this.

102
00:13:00,822 --> 00:13:06,328
According to the Buddha's understanding, so long as there's a self, there will be some form of becoming.

103
00:13:06,389 --> 00:13:07,811
There'll be some form of existence.

104
00:13:07,831 --> 00:13:10,374
So we're never going to be short on time.

105
00:13:11,075 --> 00:13:11,895
So we can relax.

106
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:20,466
Now, in terms of taking refuges and precepts,

107
00:13:21,711 --> 00:13:25,019
as our personal process of liberation.

108
00:13:26,001 --> 00:13:35,823
The Buddha here, taking refuge in the Buddha, really means having the understanding and the confidence that there is something within us to be liberated.

109
00:13:36,586 --> 00:13:40,615
That's what you're really spiritually taking your refuge in.

110
00:13:40,678 --> 00:13:46,613
And the Dharma is that specific teaching which will help you to attain that liberation.

111
00:13:48,236 --> 00:13:55,312
And the Sangha, really you can extend it to anybody and everybody who is actually helping you on the path.

112
00:13:57,756 --> 00:14:01,261
So that's the purpose of taking these refuges and precepts.

113
00:14:01,282 --> 00:14:11,654
Now, for those of you who haven't taken them before, who might like to take them, remember that it's not that you have to take them for life or anything like that.

114
00:14:12,316 --> 00:14:15,058
One takes them with an honest heart.

115
00:14:16,600 --> 00:14:24,051
It's interesting because when you join the order, when you become a monk or a nun in the Buddhist order, in the whole ceremony,

116
00:14:25,600 --> 00:14:27,365
There's no time mentioned.

117
00:14:28,528 --> 00:14:38,453
There's no question about how long do you expect to stay, or there's no vow that I will be in the order until death do us part.

118
00:14:39,456 --> 00:14:41,701
There isn't anything like that.

119
00:14:41,682 --> 00:14:46,970
So that means that it's a constant reaffirmation every day.

120
00:14:47,009 --> 00:14:52,739
You have to reaffirm, reconfirm your commitment to the monastic order.

121
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,625
And that's exactly the same with these refuges and precepts.

122
00:14:56,645 --> 00:15:03,336
So it's like every day there should be a point where you reconfirm your commitment to the spiritual life.

123
00:15:05,947 --> 00:15:23,791
So what we'll do is just take a little bit of silence and during that time, you know, just contemplate what taking refuges and precepts means to you and give it your own particular meaning, see?

124
00:15:23,811 --> 00:15:34,926
So that when we take it, it's actually something that is directly impinging and affecting, hopefully for the better, your life, your lifestyle, okay?

125
00:15:36,745 --> 00:15:40,090
So if we can just sit quietly for a few minutes.

126
00:18:25,816 --> 00:18:32,906
The next part is to undertake the five training rules.

127
00:18:33,426 --> 00:18:44,678
So the understanding here, the sikāpada, the footsteps of training, they're not commandments, they're not thou shalt not, they are I undertake the training rule.

128
00:18:45,739 --> 00:18:54,207
And what I think we have to understand is that virtue and the awakening come together.

129
00:18:54,287 --> 00:18:56,008
You can't have the one without the other.

130
00:18:56,489 --> 00:18:59,771
You can't have a Buddha caught shoplifting.

131
00:18:59,751 --> 00:19:02,336
It just doesn't strike you as true.

132
00:19:03,640 --> 00:19:05,403
There's something odd about that.

133
00:19:05,423 --> 00:19:12,758
So this purification of our morality, purification of our intention, that's what it basically is.

134
00:19:12,798 --> 00:19:18,648
The purification of our intention runs hand in hand with the process of insight.

135
00:19:19,611 --> 00:19:21,996
And one of the...

136
00:19:22,651 --> 00:19:33,041
one of the effects of insight is to actually see how moral actions actually causes suffering.

137
00:19:33,061 --> 00:19:38,988
We're pretty clear about things like guilt and shame and remorse and all that.

138
00:19:39,828 --> 00:19:52,201
But also, whenever we do harm, there's also the pain within us, eventually, of knowing that we've caused, we've been at least a catalyst for somebody else's suffering.

139
00:19:52,182 --> 00:19:57,196
and that can be quite painful for us to actually deal with.

140
00:19:58,712 --> 00:20:27,977
what we need to do is to keep making that resolution of following these precepts as best we can we can't expect to follow them absolutely perfectly because we don't have that perfection of mind but at least on a gross level most of us I think have stopped murdering and thieving so it's more on the more subtle levels of doing harm that we can become more aware of our actions

141
00:20:29,424 --> 00:20:38,145
When it comes to, you know, the one that I think a lot of people have difficulty with is not to take intoxicating drinks and drugs.

142
00:20:38,606 --> 00:20:44,801
And we live in a culture where, you know, taking a drop of alcohol is quite acceptable.

143
00:20:44,781 --> 00:21:03,343
So it's up to you really to decide as to what you feel is allowable, and to know that whenever consciousness is distorted in any way, then there's always a possibility of doing something which is harmful.

144
00:21:04,083 --> 00:21:09,169
So it's up to us to decide at what level we want to take these trainings.

145
00:21:10,567 --> 00:21:29,502
so the conjunction of virtue and understanding come together you can't have the one without the other and again the Buddha manifests this by this movement from right understanding to right attitude

146
00:21:29,669 --> 00:21:33,974
and from right attitude into right speech, right action, and right livelihood.

147
00:21:34,895 --> 00:21:39,280
And remember that this path reverts upon itself.

148
00:21:39,382 --> 00:21:43,186
You can start with right livelihood and it will affect your attitude.

149
00:21:43,846 --> 00:21:46,490
So it doesn't really matter what you do.

150
00:21:47,211 --> 00:21:50,496
You know that old song, it ain't what you do, it's the way that you do it.

151
00:21:50,476 --> 00:22:01,057
it's actually having a right intention that your work is of service, and that immediately begins to affect the heart base as a compassion.

152
00:22:01,898 --> 00:22:11,116
And compassion, when we begin to experience compassion and love that way, we begin to understand it as interconnectedness.

153
00:22:11,096 --> 00:22:24,111
And from interconnectedness you begin to understand that this idea of me is really a composite which is affected by all my relationships.

154
00:22:24,192 --> 00:22:29,182
So it takes away this sense of I, begins to undermine the sense of I.

155
00:22:29,983 --> 00:22:37,117
And the I is always this sense of self, is always expressing itself, is always trying to find happiness for itself.

156
00:22:37,940 --> 00:22:46,115
So when we go out into work as a selfless attitude, as an attitude of selflessness,

157
00:22:46,500 --> 00:22:55,515
of service that immediately undermines the self as something which is always seeking its own pleasure.

158
00:22:56,305 --> 00:23:06,885
So this movement from understanding into the heart as attitude and outwards as action, you can take it both ways.

159
00:23:07,768 --> 00:23:17,587
And whatever your work is, it's for us to find the reason for doing it, which will be a virtuous reason,

160
00:23:17,567 --> 00:23:21,472
and the effect upon the heart and the mind will just naturally arise.

161
00:23:22,054 --> 00:23:32,287
Just as the other way, when we sit in meditation with Vipassana and there's some insight, it has an effect on our attitude and eventually into the way we work.

162
00:23:32,307 --> 00:23:45,364
So it doesn't matter where you start on this particular path, whether it's as an understanding or as a right attitude or as a right action, the effect will be systemic.

163
00:23:46,103 --> 00:24:02,242
So the thing about the precepts is to just take them at your own level of understanding, at your own level of commitment, constantly just pushing yourself gently towards a more and more virtuous life.

164
00:24:03,443 --> 00:24:06,567
Don't put unnecessary pressure on you.

165
00:24:06,909 --> 00:24:09,731
There's no need to put unnecessary pressure on ourselves.

166
00:24:10,301 --> 00:24:13,605
You always work from the base where you are and you gently lean.

167
00:24:13,625 --> 00:24:16,788
So this is the Buddha's words, to incline towards Mibbana.

168
00:24:17,288 --> 00:24:20,611
So if you lean forward fine enough, you take a step.

169
00:24:20,871 --> 00:24:21,571
See?

170
00:24:21,592 --> 00:24:25,255
All you've got to do is just lean in the right direction.

171
00:24:25,875 --> 00:24:39,346
So let's just spend a few minutes, just a couple of minutes there, just reflecting upon our virtue and what it means to take the precepts.

172
00:24:52,742 --> 00:24:53,220
Thank you.

173
00:26:31,089 --> 00:26:33,432
So what we can do now is actually take them.

174
00:26:35,394 --> 00:26:44,222
We'll also read the verses at the back of the sheet, which is basically our vipassana verses, and then some inspiring verses from the Buddha.

175
00:26:44,942 --> 00:26:50,588
And then before we say sadhu sadhu, we'll get Mickey to pour this water while I do a little chanting.

176
00:26:51,569 --> 00:26:58,936
And that's the basic chant of offering goodwill to all beings.

177
00:26:58,916 --> 00:27:10,548
and during that time you can offer whatever merit you have for the benefit of whomever you wish, but it's always good to end off with all beings, that's all.

178
00:27:10,568 --> 00:27:10,769
Okay.

179
00:27:12,210 --> 00:27:21,318
So, in the fashion of taking reference and precepts, you have to chant it after me.

180
00:27:22,059 --> 00:27:25,042
Okay.

181
00:27:26,997 --> 00:27:29,901
Namo tassa bhagavato.

182
00:27:29,921 --> 00:27:30,682
Hold on, stop.

183
00:27:30,702 --> 00:27:32,826
You have to chant it after me.

184
00:27:32,846 --> 00:27:34,729
Because I'm passing it on to you.

185
00:27:37,071 --> 00:27:44,163
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa.

186
00:27:45,424 --> 00:27:52,194
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa.

187
00:27:53,541 --> 00:28:18,115
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambudassa

